\cf6 \uc0\u9210 \cf3  Good question \'97 you're right that fresh snowfall does bump scores, and it     \
  does. Just not through \cf10 score_snow_depth\cf3 . Here's the distinction:              \
                                                                                \
  
\f1\b \cf10 score_snow_depth(depth_in)\cf3  \'97 only takes depth, no snowfall input
\f0\b0               \
                                                                                \
  This function scores base depth quality only. The original version had a      \
  "rescue clause" where >= 8" of fresh snow in 72hrs could rescue a thin base\
  score up to 0.2. That was removed because fresh snowfall already has its own  \
  dedicated place in the pipeline.                          \
\
  
\f1\b Fresh snowfall is accounted for in two other places:
\f0\b0                           \
   \
  1. 
\f1\b \cf10 score_snowfall(snowfall_72hr_in)
\f0\b0 \cf3  in \cf10 weather_score.R\cf3  \'97 fresh snow gets its  \
  own full weighted component in the weather composite (weighted 0.15\'960.40\
  depending on ability). An expert gets 40% of their weather score from this    \
  alone.                                                    \
  2. 
\f1\b \cf10 apply_snowfall_bump(terrain_pcts, snowfall_72hr_in)
\f0\b0 \cf3  in \cf10 terrain_open_score.R\cf3 \
   \'97 fresh snow bumps up the terrain open percentages per tier (up to +15% for  \
  12"+ of snow), before the final accessibility score is calculated.\
                                                                                \
  So the logic you remember is still there \'97 fresh snow absolutely improves     \
  scores. It's just that it was cleaner to give it its own dedicated function\
  rather than have \cf10 score_snow_depth\cf3  try to do double duty. The README function  \
  signature \cf10 score_snow_depth(depth_in)\cf3  is correct as-is.    \
